			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">Sorry for the delay!  Hope you enjoy this.
<br />

<br />
<span style="font-style: italic">Continued...</span>
<br />

<br />
Before the first arrow made contact with the beast she had a second placed and loaded on the bow.  She stood now, ready for the coming of the enraged giant.  She’d hoped that with a shot to the neck he’d be unable to call for aid, and with a little luck she’d pierce a vital vessel, but it was impossible to tell from this distance.
<br />

<br />
Fear and pain were gone from her body and mind now, as adrenaline pumped through her veins.  She did not feel the incredible burning in her fingers caused by the snap of the bowstring upon release of the arrow, however much of the skin had been torn from her fingertips and fresh blood was running down the line, now.  The strength of this bow would take a heavy toll on her body over time, if she chose to use it with any frequency.  But, all this was unimportant now, as she stood waiting, perspiration rolling slowly over her temple and down her cheek despite the air around her, still untouched by the warmth of the morning sun.
<br />

<br />
Any forced waiting – waiting that she had not planned or anticipated made Efinia’s mind race.  She did not fight well when she had time to think.  Doubt and uncertainty had developed a habit of creeping their way into her thoughts given the opportunity.  Perhaps the arrow had caught a breeze and had flown over his head.  Perhaps something had disrupted its flight and weakened its power so that it had not even pierced the giant’s armor.  Or, worse yet, he may have been rounding up a small retaliation force as she stood idle, for the fog had thickened and she could no longer see as clearly.  With each question she asked herself, another bead of sweat fell from her chin.  With each drop, she became more and more aware of the pain screaming through her body.
<br />

<br />
She knew she had to move, for the patrolling giants would be coming out of their slumbers soon.  She had to end this encounter before any additional hostiles found her.  She carefully eased the bowstring to its resting position, and replaced the arrow in her quiver.  Slinging the bow again over her shoulder, she knelt down and closed her eyes, calming herself once again in meditation, but still very aware of the ever-present dangers around her.  Her body remained completely still, but the surface of her eyelids was wild with movement; her eyes behind them searching her soul, gathering power from Tunare.
<br />

<br />
She began to whisper the words of ancient Elvish, summoning forth powers from the planes.  With each word spoken the sound grew, as if the same choir of faeries was with her once again.  She raised her arms from her sides slowly, palms up as she slowly began to rise from her knees, continuing the chants.
<br />

<br />
<span style="font-style: italic">Tunare, anta nin laita nol e valar
<br />
Ahya hroa linta e finda vanya
<br />
Mirroanwi s&#365;re vea lupina
<br />

<br />
	Tunare, bless me with wisdom and power
<br />
	Give me the pale fur, so I may be swift
<br />
	Let me run with the wind as the wolf</span>
<br />

<br />
	As the final verse left her mouth a small emerald charm at her wrist began to glow brighter, and brighter until the light from it was almost blinding.  She became surrounded by a thick green mist, swirling faster and faster around her, encasing her body so tightly in the eerie wind that her form was barely distinguishable from outside the cloud.  The mist lifted her from the ground as she relaxed her entire body.  She hung limp, being easily manipulated by the thickening maelstrom of air as if she’d no bones at all.  Behind the greenish veil her skin began to peel and break, nails growing thick and hard.  Her bronze skin lightened as a thin layer of gray hair spread across it.  Her lower jaw began to protrude while the teeth resting in it lengthened and sharpened.  Her torso narrowed, and chest lowered.  Her knees seemed to hyperextend, and then lock almost naturally into a ‘reversed’ position, close to her upper body now.
<br />
	
<br />
	The mist cleared as fast as it had appeared, and in its stead stood a powerful and proud white wolf, its coat sleek and thick, almost like polished silver in appearance.  The eyes were sharp and blue as the skies of Erollisi, yet deep and foreboding; the wisdom behind them almost as intimidating as the savage fangs lining her jaw.
<br />

<br />
	The entire transformation had taken no more than a few seconds, but the images would have been so utterly grotesque to any common onlooker, he or she surely would have returned at least his breakfast to Tunare after witnessing it.  But, the product of this freakish phenomenon was nothing less than breathtaking.  Efinia had taken the form of the ancient great white wolves of the Northlands, and thus she now also possessed in addition to her own, all of their many strengths.  She had their unmatched speed, their eyesight, their fearlessness…  But she had also inherited the trait that would possibly prove to be most valuable here – a reckless abandon and deadly instinct.
<br />

<br />
	She crouched slightly on her hind legs, then leapt to full speed seemingly without perceptible acceleration.  Dodging trees and shrubs with no effort, ducking under fallen logs, and all the while making not a sound.  From a distance, one could only see random flashes of reflected light in the early morning sun, moving with the speed of a Highland Prism Wisp along the forest floor.
<br />

<br />
	As she neared the clearing where the foreman had stood she jumped onto the rugged trunk of an Elder Zek Redleaf, and crept slowly up towards the branches to survey silently over the land.  She saw the other giant still standing there, in a lazy and possibly drunken slumber, but had no sense of the foreman’s location.  As she looked more closely for signs of trampled saplings or startled fauna, she noticed a thin layer of dust hanging over the ground at the feet of the standing giant.  As a light breeze made its way over the base of the forest, the low-lying haze of dust began to clear.  Through her perfect canine eyes she could clearly make out that unmistakable whip, under which she saw the faintest glint of an insignia badge, an insignia she knew to be the crest of a Kromzek Foreman.
<br />

<br />
	She looked one more time at the remaining giant, and affirmed that his languor was deep enough for her to complete her business and retreat unnoticed.  She sprung from her perch to the ground near the fallen giant.  Her doubts that he was dead were ignored in favor of the incredible ecstasy she was beginning to feel that he might indeed have been.
<br />

<br />
She inched closer to the body and around, nearer the torso and head.  The distinct scent of fresh blood lingered around her, now and she could see the result of her assault.  The mithril tip of her arrow was protruding from the cheek of the giant she could now confirm as being no more.  The arrowhead and upper shaft were covered in a thick gore that slowly spilled down the face of the cadaver.  From the mouth there was still a light rhythmic gurgling sound as the heart tried in vain to circulate the life fluid that could now no longer be circulated, but only let.
<br />

<br />
Never had she imagined such mutilation being caused from one single arrow, even of the finest mithril, especially against a frost giant of Kael Drakkel, a Foreman, nonetheless!  The skulls of the Kromzek were far thicker than any other species on Velious, that was widely held to be fact.  As she continued to marvel at the power of her bow, she began to remove the head of the giant, once again, she in her familiar Elven form.  The care with which she made the perfect cuts was bizarre and unnatural when seen with the bloody sinews and torn flesh of her victim.  Her efficiency and precision did not prevent liberal amounts of blood from spilling to the earth.
<br />

<br />
Aside from the additional sawing needed to disconnect the spine, the job was as clean as it could have been.  She removed the coif from the head, and placed it a large haversack.  She also took the insignia from his chest, and his coin purse, which she noted, weighed more than her new bow.
<br />

<br />
Because the trophy she’d so gingerly removed from the giant’s shoulders was so immense (the head came midway up her thigh), she wouldn’t be able to carry it back to the Faydark.  Fortunately, there was no need, for she’d made good friends over the centuries.  From one of these friends she’d been given a priceless trinket - one that had saved her from countless entanglements.  The powers to journey almost instantly back to Kelethin, the tree-city of the Wood Elves, were harbored in a small, seemingly plain clay idol of Tunare.  She held the statue in her hand.  Just as she started to close her eyes in prayer she noticed something at her feet.  A tiny shrub with bright green, almost perfectly round leaves.  There was only one plant she’d encountered in all of her travels that had perfectly round leaves like this one.  It was the Yew Fern, the leaves of which were highly sought-after, not only for their healing powers, but also for tannins, cures and for its less talked-about intoxicating effects when inhaled.
<br />

<br />
She knelt down slowly and deliberately, burdened by the weight and cumber of her new acquisitions, and uprooted the small fern.  She placed it into a small bag hanging from her belt where she kept more fragile items she’d foraged over the lands.  She noticed the giant above her begin snorting and hacking as he lazily came out of his stupor.  She thought of the utter confusion he’d feel when he became fully aware, and smiled to herself.  She closed her eyes, and grasped the idol.  As she whispered her prayers she removed a coin from her purse and flipped it high into the air.  It caught the morning sun on its face, and reflected the bright gold color of the metal.  The coin flipped over and over in the damp air and landed silently on the corpse’s belly.  But, by that time Efinia was gone.
<br />

<br />
*
<br />

<br />
The builder noticed a flash of light from below him and peered down, mind still hazy from his long nap.  And oh, what a satisfying nap it was!  His eyes widened and he smiled foolishly as he knelt closer, realizing that it was a gold piece he’d seen.  His heart racing in anticipation of the unexpected payment bonus, it took him a few seconds to notice the limp hand of his site overseer resting next to it.  The shriek that sounded could be heard through the entire forest, and in response its canopy unleashed a mass of birds into the indigo early morning skies.
<br />

<br />

<br />
<span style="font-style: italic">To be continued...</span><br />_________________<br /><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=84779" target="_blank" class="postlink">Mystikefini Ali</a>
