			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">A shorter addition...  Enjoy! <img src="images/smiles/icon_wink.gif" alt="icon_wink.gif" border="0" />  
<br />

<br />

<br />
<span style="font-style: italic">Continued...</span>
<br />

<br />

<br />
Arziyk Far’Ligt squinted as the sun snuck from behind a tall Antonican Sycamore.  A bead of sweat crept down the corner of his brow and over his temple, his cobalt skin glistening in the intense heat.  He rode slowly and lackadaisically, as if he’d not a care in the world.  His valorous mount was an old mare he’d borrowed from the Militia stables.  He’d fully intended to return it to those poorly trained and unwitting soldiers - he’d just leave the returning up to the horse.
<br />

<br />
His destination was the Eastern horizon, and then the horizon beyond that, as it would continue until he found what he was seeking.  It had evaded him for the better part of the last 400 years.  It was the thing of legends; a weapon born of such craftsmanship that only the most skilled of wielders could even begin to bring forth its destructive potential.  He’d held it once, long ago, the memory now causing his hands to tighten into a fist.  It teased and taunted him from the Faydark, like a tortured banshee in the depths of his soul, unrelenting in its screams.
<br />

<br />
	The horse padded along through the high grasses of the Commonlands.  Arziyk was careful to stay off the beaten path, so as to avoid any unnecessary confrontation with any other travelers.  He certainly had no qualms about slaughtering a few human peons every now and again, but the Militia had been out in force for the past few weeks, since the assault on the Storm Reaper trade caravan from Rivervale.  The number of Halfling corpses said to have been found that evening rose daily as the word spread.  Descriptions of events in this land tended to augment themselves as they passed from mouth to ear, and so on.  The brutality with which the massacre was carried out pointed unwaveringly to the Dark Elves of Neriak as being the culprits, and no one, Elves included, gave any reason to believe otherwise.
<br />

<br />
	A perverse grin crossed the face of the lone Tier’Dal rider as he recalled the events of the last moon.  He was proud of the rumors telling of an entire group of as many as 5 Dark Elven rogues attacking the caravan.  Even the Halflings of the Storm Reapers were hardly worthy of being called fighters, let alone adversaries.  They were renowned for their laziness and dreamer attitudes; getting fat on nuts and wine while envisioning the gold and jewels they would procure when they eventually rolled off their backs to find it.  Such sloth and delusions of grandeur did, however combine to make talented thieves and pickpockets.  The broach he now wore on his cloak reminded him of that.
<br />

<br />
The ruby-encrusted pendant had once belonged to a Dwarven baron, and apparently held powers of protection that had kept that baron safe longer than any Dwarf before him.  Arziyk was curious to discover what it could do for his own life expectancy - cutting short those of the Halflings mattered not to the Dark Elf.
<br />

<br />
As he rode on, he noticed the path he’d been paralleling forked up ahead by 500 paces.  Through the trees he could make out a small outpost acting as a checkpoint he assumed meant for those travelers heading into Freeport for passage across the sea.  The stench of human sweat and dirt penetrated his nostrils, growing as he neared the crossroads.   He could begin to hear the muffled sounds of that crude human dialect of the Common Tongue, which was vile enough as it was.
<br />

<br />
He gently guided the horse south, away from the path, and away from the humans, heading towards the hills of the Ro Desert.  The caves there were notorious for acting as a hub for travelers and traders; a hub where only the shadiest of characters could conduct only the shadiest of business without fear of intrusion or disruption by any enforcers of any law.  The type of folk that chose to deal in those hills made any attempt at legal jurisdiction far too dangerous a proposition to be worthwhile.  Arziyk was reassured as he turned to those hills, certain that among such people, he would pass virtually unnoticed.
<br />

<br />

<br />
